                            "spans": [
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        224,
                                        2775,
                                        1208,
                                        2973
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "There has recently been a surge of interest in deep learning on molecules. Boltzmann generators (Noé et al., 2019; Köhler et al., 2021) use flows to sample from the Boltzmann distribution. There are two ways to generate samples with"
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ],
                    "index": 4
                },
                {
                    "bbox": [
                        1277,
                        280,
                        2259,
                        874
                    ],
                    "type": "text",
                    "lines": [
                        {
                            "bbox": [
                                1277,
                                280,
                                2259,
                                874
                            ],
                            "spans": [
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1277,
                                        280,
                                        2259,
                                        874
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "Boltzmann Generators: (i) Produce i.i.d. samples from the flow and use statistical reweighting to debias expectation values. (ii) Use the Boltzmann generator in an MCMC framework (Dibak et al., 2022), as in Timewarp. As Boltzmann generators rely on internal coordinates, they do not generalise to multiple proteins, unlike Timewarp. Recently, Xu et al. (2022) proposed GeoDiff, a diffusion model that predicts molecular conformations from a molecular graph. Like Timewarp, GeoDiff works in Cartesian coordinates and generalises to unseen molecules. However, GeoDiff was not applied to proteins, but small molecules, and does not target the Boltzmann distribution."
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ],
                    "index": 5
                },
                {
                    "bbox": [
                        1277,
                        904,
                        2261,
                        1699
                    ],
                    "type": "text",
                    "lines": [
                        {
                            "bbox": [
                                1277,
                                904,
                                2261,
                                1699
                            ],
                            "spans": [
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1277,
                                        904,
                                        2261,
                                        1699
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "Markov state models (MSMs) (Prinz et al., 2011; Swope et al., 2004; Husic & Pande, 2018) are another related technique. MSMs work by running many short MD simulations, which are used to define a discrete state space, along with an estimated transition probability matrix. Similarly to Timewarp, MSMs estimate the transition probability between the state at a time "
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1277,
                                        904,
                                        2261,
                                        1699
                                    ],
                                    "type": "inline_equation",
                                    "content": "t"
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1277,
                                        904,
                                        2261,
                                        1699
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": " and the time "
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1277,
                                        904,
                                        2261,
                                        1699
                                    ],
                                    "type": "inline_equation",
                                    "content": "t - \\tau"
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1277,
                                        904,
                                        2261,
                                        1699
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": " where "
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1277,
                                        904,
                                        2261,
                                        1699
                                    ],
                                    "type": "inline_equation",
                                    "content": "\\tau \\gg \\Delta t"
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1277,
                                        904,
                                        2261,
                                        1699
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": ". Recent work has applied deep learning to MSMs, leading to VAMPnets (Mardt et al., 2018) and deep generative MSMs (Wu et al., 2018), which replace the MSM data- processing pipeline with deep networks. In contrast to Timewarp, these models are not transferable: new MD simulations have to be performed, and new networks trained, for each molecular system. Furthermore, MSMs model the dynamics in a coarse- grained, discrete state space, rather than in the all- atom coordinate representation as with Timewarp."
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ],
                    "index": 6
                },
                {
                    "bbox": [
                        1277,
